The \(n\)th term of a geometric sequence is given by  
\[
a_n = a_1\,r^{\,n-1}.
\]  
Here \(a_1=81\), \(r=\tfrac13\), and we want \(a_{13}\).  Thus  
\[
a_{13} = 81\Bigl(\tfrac13\Bigr)^{12}
      = 81\;\big/\,3^{12}
      = \frac{3^4}{3^{12}}
      = \frac1{3^8}
      = \frac1{6561}.
\]  
So the thirteenth term is \(\boxed{\tfrac1{6561}}\).

The \(n\)th term of a geometric sequence with first term \(a_1\) and ratio \(r\) is

\[a_n \;=\; a_1\,r^{\,n-1}.\]

Here \(a_1=256\), \(r=\tfrac14\), and \(n=12\), so

\[
a_{12}
=256\Bigl(\tfrac14\Bigr)^{11}
=\frac{256}{4^{11}}
=\frac{256}{4\,194\,304}
=\frac1{16\,384}.
\]

This is a geometric series with first term \(a=64\) and common ratio  
\[
r=\frac{16}{64}=\frac14.
\]  
Since \(\lvert r\rvert<1\), the infinite‐sum formula applies:  
\[
S=\frac{a}{1-r}
=\frac{64}{1-\tfrac14}
=\frac{64}{\tfrac34}
=\frac{64\cdot4}{3}
=\frac{256}{3}.
\]  
Answer: \(\displaystyle \frac{256}{3}.\)
